My question is related to the bound on the variance of an estimation of a parameter that can take only a finite set of values. I copy and paste what is written on wikipedia to have a common starting point and give a first example related to a parameter belonging to a continuous set. Suppose $	heta$ is an unknown deterministic parameter which is to be estimated from measurements x, distributed according to some probability density function $f(x;	heta)$. The variance of any unbiased estimator $\hat{	heta}$ of $	heta$ is then bounded by the reciprocal of the Fisher information $I(	heta)$: $\mathrm{var}(\hat{	heta}) \geq  rac{1}{I(	heta)}$ $I(	heta) = \mathrm{E}  \left[   \left(     rac{\partial \ell(x;	heta)}{\partial	heta}   ight)^2  ight] = -\mathrm{E}\left[  rac{\partial^2 \ell(x;	heta)}{\partial	heta^2} ight]$ and $\ell(x;	heta)=\log  (f(x;	heta))$ is the natural logarithm of the likelihood function and $\mathrm{E}$ denotes the expected value (over x). As a simple case we can consider the estimation of a constant $	heta \in \mathbf{R}$ in an AWGN system (Additive White Gaussian Noise). We measure $x=	heta+ 
u$ where $	heta$ is our constant and $
u$ is a gaussian random variable with zero mean and variance $\sigma^2_{
u}$ It is a known result that given a set of $N$ measurements $x[n], n=[0,...N-1]$ in a situation that can be modelled as $x[n]=s[n;	heta]+
u[n]$ where $
u[n]$ is a set of i.i.d gaussian random variable $\sim N(0,\sigma^2_{
u})$ the variance of the estimator is $\mathrm{var}(\hat{	heta}) \geq \sigma^2_{
u}(\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}( rac{\partial s[n;	heta]}{\partial 	heta})^2)^{-1}$ In this simple case the output of our ML estimator is simply $\hat{	heta}=x$ and the variance of the estimation is  $\sigma^2_{
u}$ Now this is a simple case and the calculation of the derivative it's easy and we have only one measurement (N=1) $s[n,	heta]=	heta ightarrow  rac{\partial s[n;	heta]}{\partial 	heta}=1$ I finally concluded my introduction,sorry if it was boring. Now i introduce my question: Suppose that you have a parameter that can take only a finite set of values. For example only two values (-1,+1); $	heta \in$ {-1;+1} If i'd ask you to create an estimator for this parameter it would simply be a threshold detector: $x>0 ightarrow \hat{	heta}=+1$ $x<0 ightarrow \hat{	heta}=-1$ We can also evaluate the variance of this estimator. But what about a general theoretical minimum variance for an estimator of a parameter that can take only a finite set of values? In this case the concept of derivative does not hold since it does not exist: $ rac{\partial s[n;	heta]}{\partial 	heta}$ cannot be calculated as the limit of the variation of the function $x[n;	heta]$ as the increment of $	heta$ goes to zero. Is it something known in literature? Do i have to switch to a different kind of calculus such as quantum calculus? Thank in advance to everybody for your precious help.

